A Formal Theory of Rare Signal Preservation and Latent Subspace Specialization at the 10¹³+ Parameter Scale

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

Abstract
We provide a rigorous mathematical framework explaining how ultra-large models ($D \gg \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$, empirically hypothesized near $10^{13}$ parameters) preserve and utilize rare, logically coherent signals (e.g., niche academic research) despite their vanishing frequency in the training data. The theory rests on three pillars: (1) block-diagonal dominance of the Fisher Information Matrix in the decoupling regime, enabling interference-free Natural Gradient updates; (2) an implicit flatness regularization of Stochastic Gradient Descent that favors compressed generative rules over memorization; and (3) stabilization via marginal predictive utility across the broader data distribution. We prove that under these conditions, a model converges to the generative grammar of the rare signal and exhibits compositional generalization via linear recombination in the decoupled latent space. The framework is purely theoretical but consistent with empirical observations in 10T-scale language models, and is supported by a synthetic validation protocol outlined in the appendices.

---

1. Introduction

The scaling of neural network parameter counts beyond $10^{13}$ has revealed emergent capabilities not present in smaller models, including the apparent retention and synthesis of niche, highly structured knowledge. A paradox arises: how can a model internalize the content of a document seen only a handful of times—such as an esoteric paper on Finite State Automata (FSA) or Measure-Theoretic Event Boundary Segmentation (MEBS)—when the training corpus is dominated by high-frequency, generic text? Traditional learning theory suggests such rare signals should be treated as noise and diluted.

We resolve this paradox by formalizing the transition from dilution to decoupling in the ultra-overparameterized regime. Using tools from information geometry, implicit regularization, and dynamical systems, we show that mathematically rigorous rare signals become attractor states in the loss landscape, preserved not by frequency but by their compression efficiency and predictive utility.

Our analysis focuses on the pre-training phase; subsequent fine-tuning or RLHF can be viewed as bounded perturbations acting on these established subspaces. Crucially, the framework applies strictly to logically coherent rare signals: high-entropy or structurally random rare sequences do not minimize description length and thus fail to form stable manifolds under the flatness pressure of SGD.

Motivation from Scaling Laws. Recent work on neural scaling laws has identified distinct regimes as data and parameters scale (Bahri et al., 2021). The "resolution-limited" regime emerges when models effectively resolve a smooth data manifold. We propose that at $D \sim 10^{13}$, the parameter count exceeds the intrinsic dimension of web data, triggering a phase transition in the Fisher Information Matrix that enables rare-signal preservation. The quantization model of Michaud et al. (2023) further suggests that capabilities emerge as discrete chunks, consistent with the formation of isolated grammar subspaces.

Related Work. The flat-minima hypothesis dates to Hochreiter & Schmidhuber (1997), with modern SGD analysis by Smith et al. (2021). The connection between Fisher Information Matrix spectrum and generalization was studied by Karakida et al. (2021). Our decoupling regime is conceptually related to the "resolution-limited" scaling regime of Bahri et al. (2021) and to the quantization model of Michaud et al. (2023). Linear representation of concepts in transformer residual streams has been empirically demonstrated for belief states (Oldenziel et al., 2024). The natural gradient framework originates with Amari (1998).

