2. Geometric Foundations: The Decoupling Limit

Let $f_\theta: \mathcal{X} \to \mathcal{Y}$ be a model parameterized by $\theta \in \mathbb{R}^D$. The training objective is the expected loss under the data distribution $P_{\text{data}}$:
\mathcal{L}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{x \sim P_{\text{data}}} \left[ \ell(f_\theta(x), y) \right]

Definition 2.1 (Fisher Information Matrix).
For losses derived from the negative log-likelihood (e.g., cross-entropy), the gradient satisfies $\nabla_\theta \ell = -\nabla_\theta \log p_\theta(y|x)$. The Fisher Information Matrix (FIM) $F(\theta)$ captures the local curvature of the KL-divergence in parameter space:
F(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{x \sim P_{\text{data}}} \left[ \nabla_\theta \log p_\theta(y|x) \, \nabla_\theta \log p_\theta(y|x)^T \right] = \mathbb{E}_{x} \left[ \nabla_\theta \ell \, \nabla_\theta \ell^T \right]

Definition 2.2 (Dilution Regime).
When $D \ll \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$, the FIM $F(\theta)$ is dense and low-rank. The gradient of a rare signal $x_{\text{rare}}$ (frequency $\epsilon \to 0$) lies almost entirely in the span of gradients from high-density samples. Consequently, its Natural Gradient update $\tilde{\nabla}_\theta \mathcal{L} = F(\theta)^{-1} \nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}$ fails to isolate the rare concept, causing destructive interference and dilution into the dominant mode.

Definition 2.3 (Decoupling Regime).
In the ultra-overparameterized limit $D \gg \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$ (empirically hypothesized near $D \sim 10^{13}$ for web-scale corpora), the FIM $F(\theta)$ exhibits Block-Diagonal Dominance. Let $\mathcal{M}_i$ denote the concept manifold defined by the dominant eigenspace of $F(\theta)$ above a spectral threshold $\tau > 0$, and let $\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i}$ be the orthogonal projector onto this subspace. For any two logically distinct concepts $i \neq j$:
\left\| \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i} F(\theta) \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_j} \right\|_F \leq \epsilon(D) \ll \|F(\theta)\|_F \quad \text{with} \quad \epsilon(D) \to 0 \text{ as } D \to \infty


where $\text{eff}(P_{\text{data}}) := \left( \sum_k \lambda_k \right)^2 / \sum_k \lambda_k^2$ is the participation ratio of the FIM eigenvalues, capturing the intrinsic dimensionality of the data manifold.

Justification. This spectral behavior is consistent with mean-field analysis of FIMs in overparameterized networks, where most eigenvalues collapse to zero while a few large eigenvalues dominate (Karakida et al., 2021). The participation ratio quantifies this collapse. Moreover, theoretical work on overparameterized quantum neural networks has proven that when $D > M_c$ (a critical model size), the FIM rank saturates and the loss landscape undergoes a phase transition to a connected set of minima (Larocca et al., 2021). We hypothesize an analogous phase transition in large language models.

Consequence: The Natural Gradient update $\tilde{\nabla}_\theta \mathcal{L}$ for $x_{\text{rare}}$ is effectively orthogonal to the subspaces of common language. Rare signals cease to be noise; they become isolated degrees of freedom.

