Appendix A: Complete Proof of Theorem 5.1

Theorem 5.1. Under (A1) and (A2), the optimization trajectory converges to $\mathcal{M}_G$, the representation has intrinsic dimension $d \ll D$, and the model exhibits compositional generalization for any $x' \sim G$.

Proof.

Part 1 (Convergence): Consider the gradient flow $\dot{\theta}_t = -\nabla \mathcal{L}(\theta_t) + \xi_t$ with $\text{Cov}(\xi_t) \approx \frac{\eta}{B}H(\theta_t)$. Under (A2), the parameter space decomposes orthogonally into $\mathcal{M}_G \oplus \mathcal{M}_{\text{common}} \oplus \mathcal{N}$, where $\mathcal{N}$ is the nullspace of the FIM. Let $\mathcal{C}_m, \mathcal{C}_g$ be memorization and compression solutions with $\mathcal{L}(\mathcal{C}_m) \approx \mathcal{L}(\mathcal{C}_g) \approx 0$. The effective loss $\mathcal{L}_{\text{eff}} = \mathcal{L} + \frac{\eta}{2B}\text{Tr}(H)$ is strictly lower at $\mathcal{C}_g$ due to distributed curvature versus sharp token-embedding peaks. By LaSalle's Invariance Principle for stochastic differential equations, the stationary distribution concentrates on $\mathcal{M}_G$, making it the dominant attractor.

Part 2 (Dimensionality): The intrinsic dimension is $d = \text{rank}(\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} F \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G})$. Under (A1), $G$ minimizes description length, parameterizable by $d = O(\text{Kolmogorov}(G))$ primitives. The FIM eigenvalues satisfy $\lambda_k > \epsilon$ for $k \leq d$ and $\lambda_k \approx 0$ otherwise. Thus $d \ll D$.

Part 3 (Generalization): For any $x' \sim G$, the model output $f_{\theta^*}(x')$ depends only on projections onto the tangent space $\mathcal{T}_{\theta^*}\mathcal{M}_G$. By the restricted universal approximation property on the manifold, the model implements a function $\Phi_G: \mathcal{X} \to \mathcal{T}_{\theta^*}\mathcal{M}_G$ that evaluates the axioms embedded in $\mathcal{M}_G$. Since $x'$ is generated by the same grammar $G$, the logical continuation is uniquely determined. $\square$

