Appendix B: Derivation of the SGD Effective Loss

Lemma 3.1. Under $\Sigma(\theta) \preceq c \frac{\eta}{B} H(\theta)$ and small $\eta$, SGD minimizes $\mathcal{L}_{\text{eff}}(\theta) = \mathcal{L}(\theta) + \frac{\eta}{2B} \text{Tr}(H(\theta))$.

Proof. The discrete SGD update $\theta_{t+1} = \theta_t - \eta \hat{g}_t$ converges weakly to the Itô stochastic differential equation:
d\theta_t = -\nabla \mathcal{L}(\theta_t) dt + \sqrt{\frac{\eta}{B}} \Sigma(\theta_t)^{1/2} dW_t


where $\Sigma(\theta) = \mathbb{E}[(\hat{g} - \nabla \mathcal{L})(\hat{g} - \nabla \mathcal{L})^T]$ is the gradient noise covariance. Under the alignment assumption $\Sigma(\theta) \preceq c \frac{\eta}{B} H(\theta)$, the stationary distribution satisfies $p(\theta) \propto \exp\left(-\frac{2B}{\eta}\mathcal{L}(\theta)\right) \det(H(\theta))^{-1/2}$. Taking the negative logarithm and using the approximation $\log \det(H) \approx \text{Tr}(H - I)$ near minima yields $\mathcal{L}_{\text{eff}}(\theta) = \mathcal{L}(\theta) + \frac{\eta}{2B} \text{Tr}(H(\theta))$ up to an additive constant. This approximation is local and relies on Hessian-aligned noise, which has been empirically validated in overparameterized networks (Sagun et al., 2018; Karakida et al., 2021). $\square$

