Appendix C: Spectral Analysis & Block-Diagonal Dominance

Proposition C.1. For $D \gg \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$, disjoint concepts satisfy $\|\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i} F \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_j}\|_F \leq \mathcal{O}(\sqrt{\text{eff}(P)}/\sqrt{D})$ with high probability.

Proof Sketch. The empirical FIM is $F = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N g_n g_n^\top$, where $g_n = \nabla_\theta \ell(x_n)$. For semantically disjoint concepts, the gradient vectors satisfy $g_n^{(i)} \perp g_m^{(j)}$ in expectation. In $\mathbb{R}^D$, random vectors concentrate on the sphere; the inner product between independent random vectors scales as $\mathcal{O}(1/\sqrt{D})$. By matrix concentration inequalities (Tropp, 2015), the Frobenius norm of the off-diagonal block is bounded by $\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{\text{eff}(P)}/\sqrt{D})$, which vanishes as $D \to \infty$. This establishes asymptotic block-diagonality in the overparameterized limit. $\square$

