Appendix E: Linear Recombination & Error Bounds

Proposition 6.1. With $\mathcal{P}_{G_1} F \mathcal{P}_{G_2} \approx 0$, the output error satisfies $\| f_\theta(z_{\text{new}}) - \alpha f_{G_1}(z) - \beta f_{G_2}(z) \| \leq \mathcal{O}(\|\Pi_{G_1} z\|^2 \|\Pi_{G_2} z\|^2)$.

Proof. Consider a Taylor expansion of the model output in the residual stream around the zero activation:
f_\theta(z_{\text{new}}) = f(0) + J z_{\text{new}} + \frac{1}{2} z_{\text{new}}^\top H_f z_{\text{new}} + \dots


Substitute $z_{\text{new}} = \alpha \Pi_{G_1} z + \beta \Pi_{G_2} z$. The linear terms decouple due to orthogonality of the subspaces. The quadratic cross-term is $\alpha\beta (\Pi_{G_1} z)^\top H_f (\Pi_{G_2} z)$. Under the block-diagonal FIM assumption, the Hessian also exhibits block structure, so cross-terms vanish: $\Pi_{G_1} H_f \Pi_{G_2} \approx 0$. Architectural normalization (LayerNorm and residual scaling) bounds higher-order terms, yielding a second-order error in the subspace energies. $\square$

