Appendix F: Empirical Validation Protocol (No Physical Testing Performed)

We outline a synthetic validation protocol to test the theory's predictions. This is a theoretical design; no experiments were conducted.

F.1 Data Generation.

· $P_{\text{common}}$: $10^6$ sequences from a Markov chain over alphabet $\Sigma = \{0,1\}^8$.
· Rare Grammar $G$: A context-free grammar generating balanced brackets with additional logical constraints (e.g., XOR relationships between bracket types). Frequency $\epsilon \in \{10^{-5}, 10^{-6}, 10^{-7}\}$.
· Utility coupling: Inject tokens derived from $G$ into 5% of $P_{\text{common}}$ sequences to guarantee a predictive utility $\delta > 0$.

F.2 Metrics & Probes.

1. FIM Block Structure: Estimate FIM using Hutchinson's trace estimator and randomized SVD. Compute coherence $\rho = \|\mathcal{P}_G F \mathcal{P}_{\text{common}}\|_F / \|F\|_F$.
2. Hessian Trace: Compare $\text{Tr}(H)$ between a model trained normally and one forced to memorize via gradient clipping.
3. Predictive Utility: Ablate the $G$-subspace (zero out $\mathcal{P}_G \theta$) and measure $\Delta \mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}$, which should approximate $\delta$.
4. Recombination Accuracy: Evaluate perplexity and parser validity on novel sequences constrained by $G_1 \otimes G_2$.
5. Subspace Persistence: Vary weight decay $\lambda$ and verify collapse when $\lambda > \delta / \|\mathcal{P}_G \theta^*\|^2$.

F.3 Scaling Analysis.
Train models with $D \in \{10^9, 10^{10}, 10^{11}, 10^{12}, 10^{13}\}$. Predict a sharp drop in $\rho(D)$ and a flip in the memorization/compression ratio at $D \approx \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$.

